          "title": "What Is TQM?",
          "content": "Total Quality Management, commonly known as TQM, is a comprehensive approach to improving quality in a business that involves every single person in the organization, not just those who inspect products at the end of the production process. This important concept originated in Japan after World War II, thanks to the influential work of W. Edwards Deming. He taught companies that many quality issues arise from how the systems and processes are set up, rather than from workers being careless or not doing their jobs properly. TQM is based on three essential principles that guide its implementation.\nThe first principle is customer focus, which emphasizes that quality should be defined by the customer’s perspective. This means that what matters most is how customers perceive the quality of the products or services they receive. The second principle is continuous improvement, which encourages everyone in the organization to always look for better ways to do things. This mindset fosters innovation and helps businesses adapt to changing needs and challenges. Lastly, total participation is the third principle, highlighting that quality is a shared responsibility. This means that everyone in the company, from the CEO to the janitor, plays a vital role in ensuring quality standards are met. By embracing TQM, companies can enhance their products and services, ultimately leading to greater customer satisfaction and loyalty.\nContext recap: Total Quality Management, commonly known as TQM, is a comprehensive approach to improving quality in a business that involves every single person in the organization, not just those who inspect products at the end of the production process. This important concept originated in Japan after World War II, thanks to the influential work of W. Edwards Deming. He taught companies that many quality issues arise from how the systems and processes are set up, rather than from workers being careless or not doing their jobs properly.\nWhy this matters: What Is TQM? helps learners in Business connect ideas from Quality Management & Lean Operations to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
