          "content": "Six Sigma is a powerful method that organizations use to improve their processes and eliminate defects. It relies heavily on data to make informed decisions. When we talk about achieving six sigma, we mean that there are only 3.4 defects for every million opportunities, which is incredibly close to perfection! This methodology was first developed by Motorola in the 1980s, and it gained a lot of attention when General Electric, led by Jack Welch, reported saving over $2 billion in just five years by implementing Six Sigma practices. The core idea of Six Sigma is that every outcome or result is influenced by a specific process, and every process can have some variation. This variation can lead to inconsistencies in the final product or service. Therefore, the main goal of Six Sigma is to reduce this variation as much as possible. By doing so, organizations can ensure that their processes consistently meet the expectations and specifications of their customers. This not only helps in delivering high-quality products but also enhances customer satisfaction and loyalty. In summary, Six Sigma is about striving for excellence by using data to understand and improve processes, ultimately leading to better outcomes for both the organization and its customers.\nContext recap: Six Sigma is a powerful method that organizations use to improve their processes and eliminate defects. It relies heavily on data to make informed decisions. When we talk about achieving six sigma, we mean that there are only 3.4 defects for every million opportunities, which is incredibly close to perfection! This methodology was first developed by Motorola in the 1980s, and it gained a lot of attention when General Electric, led by Jack Welch, reported saving over $2 billion in just five years by implementing Six Sigma practices.\nWhy this matters: Six Sigma Fundamentals helps learners in Business connect ideas from Quality Management & Lean Operations to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
